WEBVTT

00:23.580 --> 00:24.980
IX.

00:25.600 --> 00:26.860
THE PAUNS.

00:28.580 --> 00:36.440
Sometimes, having a surfeit of human society and gossip, and worn out all my village friends,

00:37.620 --> 00:43.960
I rambled still farther westward than I habitually dwell, into yet more unfrequented parts of

00:43.960 --> 00:51.520
the town, to fresh woods and pastures new, or, while the sun was setting, made my supper

00:51.520 --> 00:58.460
of huckleberries and blueberries on Fair Haven Hill, and laid up a store for several days.

00:59.720 --> 01:05.580
The fruits do not yield their true flavor to the purchaser of them, nor to him who raises

01:05.580 --> 01:14.720
them for the market. There is but one way to obtain it, yet few take that way. If you

01:14.720 --> 01:23.860
the flavor of huckleberries, ask the cowboy or the partridge, it is a vulgar error to

01:23.860 --> 01:31.140
suppose that you have tasted huckleberries who never plucked them. A huckleberry never

01:31.140 --> 01:41.800
reaches Boston. They have not been known there since they grew on her three hills. The ambrosial

01:41.800 --> 01:48.300
and essential part of the fruit is lost, with the bloom which is rubbed off in the market

01:48.300 --> 01:58.640
cart, or they become mere provender. As long as eternal justice reigns, not one innocent

01:58.640 --> 02:02.740
huckleberry can be transported thither from the country's hills.

02:04.780 --> 02:10.000
Occasionally, after my hoeing was done for the day, I joined some impatient companion

02:10.000 --> 02:16.760
who had been fishing on the pond since morning, as silent and motionless as a duck or a floating

02:16.760 --> 02:23.780
leaf, and after practicing various kinds of philosophy, had concluded commonly by the

02:23.780 --> 02:33.140
time I arrived that he belonged to the ancient sect of Cenobites. There was one older man,

02:33.140 --> 02:38.280
an excellent fisher and skilled in all kinds of woodcraft, who was pleased to look upon

02:38.280 --> 02:44.140
my house as a building erected for the convenience of fishermen, and I was equally pleased when

02:44.140 --> 02:51.340
he sat in my doorway to arrange his lines. He at one end of the boat and I at the other,

02:51.960 --> 02:58.880
but not many words passed between us, for he had grown deaf in his later years, but

02:58.880 --> 03:05.420
he occasionally hummed a psalm, which harmonized well enough with my philosophy.

03:07.180 --> 03:13.360
Our intercourse was thus altogether one of unbroken harmony, far more pleasing to remember

03:13.360 --> 03:19.840
than if it had been carried on by speech. When, as was commonly the case, I had none

03:19.840 --> 03:25.900
to commune with, I used to raise the echoes by striking with a paddle on the side of my

03:25.900 --> 03:34.420
boat, filling the surrounding woods with circling and dilating sounds, stirring them up as the

03:34.420 --> 03:41.600
deeper of a menagerie his wild beasts, until I elicited a growl from every wooded vale

03:41.600 --> 03:49.160
and hillside. In warm evenings I frequently sat in the boat playing the flute, and saw

03:49.160 --> 03:56.640
the perch, which I seemed to have charmed, hovering around me, and the moon, traveling

03:56.640 --> 04:04.360
over the ribbed bottom, which was strewed with the wrecks of the forest. Formally I

04:04.360 --> 04:10.080
had come to this pond adventurously from time to time, in dark summer nights, with

04:10.080 --> 04:15.220
a companion, and making a fire close to the water's edge, which we thought attracted

04:15.220 --> 04:22.140
the fishes. We caught pouts with a bunch of worms strung on a thread, and when we had

04:22.140 --> 04:28.960
done far in the night, threw the burning brands high into the air like sky-rockets, which,

04:28.960 --> 04:35.640
coming down into the pond, were quenched with a loud hissing, and we were suddenly groping

04:35.640 --> 04:42.320
in total darkness. Through this whistling a tune we took our way to the haunts of men

04:42.320 --> 04:46.420
again, but now I had made my home by the shore.

04:48.900 --> 04:55.060
Sometimes after staying in a village parlor till the family had all retired, I have returned

04:55.060 --> 05:01.000
to the woods, and partly, with a view to the next day's dinner, spent the hours of

05:01.000 --> 05:08.840
midnight fishing from a boat by moonlight, serenaded by owls and foxes, and hearing from

05:08.840 --> 05:15.800
time to time the creaking note of some unknown bird close at hand. These experiences were

05:15.800 --> 05:22.640
very memorable and valuable to me. Anchored in forty feet of water, and twenty or thirty

05:22.640 --> 05:30.460
rods from the shore, surrounded sometimes by thousands of small perch and shiners, dimpling

05:30.460 --> 05:37.000
the surface with their tails in the moonlight, and communicating by a long flaxen line with

05:37.000 --> 05:45.160
mysterious nocturnal fishes, which had their dwelling forty feet below, or sometimes dragging

05:45.160 --> 05:52.460
sixty feet of line about the pond as I drifted in the gentle night breeze. Now and then feeling

05:52.460 --> 06:00.920
a slight vibration along it, indicative of some life prowling about its extremity, of

06:00.920 --> 06:09.400
dull, uncertain, blundering purpose there, and slow to make up its mind. At length you

06:09.400 --> 06:22.440
slowly raise, pulling hand over hand, some horned pout, squeaking and squirming to the

06:22.440 --> 06:30.340
especially in dark nights, when your thoughts had wandered to vast and cosmogonal themes

06:30.340 --> 06:39.520
in other spheres, to feel this faint jerk which came to interrupt your dreams and link

06:39.520 --> 06:47.400
you to nature again. It seemed as if I might next cast my line upward into the air, as

06:47.400 --> 06:55.800
well as downward into this element, which was scarcely more dense. Thus I caught two

06:55.800 --> 07:06.140
fishes, as it were, with one hook. The scenery of Walden is on a humble scale, and though

07:06.140 --> 07:13.040
very beautiful, does not approach to grandeur, nor can it much concern one who has not long

07:13.800 --> 07:21.660
or lived by its shore, yet this pond is so remarkable for its depth and purity as to

07:21.660 --> 07:30.780
merit a particular description. It is a clear and deep green well, half a mile long and

07:30.780 --> 07:36.580
a mile and three quarters in circumference, and contains about sixty-one and a half acres,

07:37.390 --> 07:45.540
a perennial spring in the midst of pine and oak woods, without any visible inlet or outlet

07:46.060 --> 07:53.880
except by the clouds and evaporation. The surrounding hills rise abruptly from the water

07:53.880 --> 08:01.180
to the height of forty to eighty feet, though on the southeast and east they attain to about

08:01.180 --> 08:06.640
one hundred and one hundred and fifty feet respectively, within a quarter and a third

08:06.640 --> 08:15.220
of a mile. They are exclusively woodland. All our Concord waters have two colors at

08:15.220 --> 08:22.720
least, one when viewed at a distance and another more proper close at hand. The hearse depends

08:22.720 --> 08:30.580
more on the light and follows the sky. In clear weather in summer they appear blue at

08:30.580 --> 08:36.580
a little distance, especially if agitated, and at a great distance all appear alike.

08:37.400 --> 08:44.940
In stormy weather they are sometimes a dark slate color. The sea, however, is said to

08:44.940 --> 08:49.980
be blue one day and green another without any perceptible change in the atmosphere.

08:51.700 --> 08:58.220
I have seen our river when, the landscape being covered with snow, both water and ice

08:58.220 --> 09:06.480
were almost as green as grass. Some consider blue to be the color of pure water, whether

09:06.480 --> 09:14.060
liquid or solid. But looking directly down into our waters from a boat they are seen

09:14.060 --> 09:22.560
to be of very different colors. Walden is blue at one time and green at another, even

09:22.560 --> 09:31.120
the same point of view. Lying between the earth and the heavens it partakes of the color

09:31.120 --> 09:39.440
of both. Viewed from a hilltop it reflects the color of the sky, but near at hand it

09:39.440 --> 09:46.020
is of a yellowish tint, next the shore where you can see the sand, then a light green,

09:46.020 --> 09:54.240
which gradually deepens to a uniform dark green in the body of the pond. In some lights,

09:54.960 --> 10:02.180
viewed even from a hilltop, it is of a vivid green next to the shore. Some have referred

10:02.180 --> 10:08.880
this to the reflection of the verger, but it is equally green there against the railroad

10:08.880 --> 10:15.380
sand bank and in the spring before the leaves are expanded, and it may be simply the result

10:15.380 --> 10:23.540
of the prevailing blue mixed with the yellow of the sand, such is the color of its iris.

10:24.700 --> 10:31.180
This is that portion also where in the spring the ice being warmed by the heat of the sun,

10:31.680 --> 10:37.600
reflected from the bottom and also transmitted through the earth, melts first and forms a

10:37.600 --> 10:45.240
canal about the still frozen middle. Like the rest of our waters, when much agitated,

10:45.860 --> 10:50.840
in clear weather, so that the surface of the waves may reflect the sky at the right angle,

10:51.620 --> 10:56.980
or because there is more light mixed with it, it appears at a little distance of a darker

10:56.980 --> 11:04.080
blue than the sky itself. And at such a time, being on its surface and looking with divided

11:04.080 --> 11:12.220
vision, so as to see the reflection, I have discerned a matchless and indescribable light

11:12.220 --> 11:21.620
blue, such as watered or changeable silks and sword blades suggest, more cerulean than

11:21.620 --> 11:29.540
the sky itself, alternating with the original dark green on the opposite sides of the waves,

11:29.540 --> 11:38.300
which last appeared but muddy in comparison. It is a vitreous greenish blue, as I remember

11:38.300 --> 11:46.380
it, like those patches of the winter sky seen through cloud vistas in the west before sundown.

11:47.380 --> 11:54.700
Yet a single glass of its water held up to the light is as colorless as an equal quantity

11:54.700 --> 12:01.180
of air. It is well known that a large plate of glass will have a green tint, owing, as

12:01.180 --> 12:10.360
the makers say, to its body, but a small piece of the same will be colorless. How large a

12:10.360 --> 12:16.320
body of Walden water would be required to reflect a green tint I have never proved.

12:17.560 --> 12:22.980
The water of our river is black, or a very dark brown to one looking directly down on

12:22.980 --> 12:29.920
it, and, like that of most ponds, imparts to the body of one bathing in it a yellowish

12:29.920 --> 12:39.200
tinge. But this water is of such crystalline purity that the body of the bather appears

12:39.200 --> 12:47.560
of an alabaster whiteness, still more unnatural, which, as the limbs are magnified and distorted

12:47.560 --> 12:54.680
withal, produces a monstrous effect, making fit studies for a Michelangelo.

12:56.700 --> 13:03.720
The water is so transparent that the bottom can easily be discerned at the depth of twenty-five

13:03.720 --> 13:11.680
or thirty feet. Paddling over it you may see, many feet beneath the surface, the schools

13:11.680 --> 13:18.080
of perch and shiners, perhaps only an inch long, yet the form are easily distinguished

13:18.080 --> 13:25.840
by their transverse bars, and you think that they must be ascetic fish that find a subsistence

13:25.840 --> 13:32.820
there. Once, in the winter, many years ago, when I had been cutting holes through the

13:32.820 --> 13:39.060
ice in order to catch pickerel, as I stepped ashore I tossed my axe back on to the ice,

13:39.060 --> 13:46.600
but, as if some evil genius had directed it, it slid four or five rods directly into one

13:46.600 --> 13:50.560
of the holes, where the water was twenty-five feet deep.

13:51.520 --> 13:58.160
Out of curiosity I laid down on the ice, and looked through the hole, until I saw the axe

13:58.160 --> 14:04.820
a little on one side standing on its head, with its helm erect and gently swaying to

14:04.820 --> 14:09.780
and fro with the pulse of the pond, and there it might have stood erect and swaying till

14:09.780 --> 14:16.340
in the course of time the handle rotted off, if I had not disturbed it. Making another

14:16.340 --> 14:22.180
hole directly over it, with an ice-chisel which I had, and cutting down the longest

14:22.180 --> 14:27.840
birch which I could find in the neighborhood with my knife, I made a slip-noose which I

14:27.840 --> 14:33.540
attached to its end, and letting it down carefully, passed it over the knob of the handle and

14:33.540 --> 14:40.540
drew it by a line along the birch, and so pulled the axe out again. The shore is composed

14:40.540 --> 14:48.100
of a belt of smooth, rounded white stones, like paving stones, except one or two short

14:48.100 --> 14:53.700
sand beaches, and is so steep that in many places a single leap will carry you into water

14:53.700 --> 15:00.200
over your head. And were it not for its remarkable transparency, that would be the last to be

15:00.200 --> 15:08.220
seen of its bottom till it rose on the opposite side. Some think it is bottomless, it is nowhere

15:08.220 --> 15:14.800
muddy, and a casual observer would say that there were no weeds at all in it, and of noticeable

15:14.800 --> 15:20.640
plants, except in the little meadows recently overflowed which do not properly belong to

15:20.640 --> 15:28.220
it, a closer scrutiny does not detect a flag, nor a bulrush, nor even a lily, yellow or

15:28.220 --> 15:35.780
white, but only a few small heart-leaves and pottomogetons, and perhaps a water target

15:35.780 --> 15:42.620
or two, all which, however, a bather might not perceive, and these plants are clean and

15:42.620 --> 15:49.460
bright like the element they grow in. The stones extend a rod or two into the water,

15:49.820 --> 15:55.560
and then the bottom is pure sand, except in the deepest part, where there is usually a

15:55.560 --> 16:00.920
little sediment, probably from the decay of the leaves which have been wafted on to it,

16:01.140 --> 16:08.120
so many successive falls, and a bright green weed is brought up on anchors even in midwinter.

16:11.200 --> 16:17.380
We have one other pond just like this, White Pond, in Nine Acre Corner, about two and a

16:17.380 --> 16:23.800
half miles westerly, but, though I am acquainted with most of the ponds within a dozen miles

16:23.800 --> 16:31.920
of this centre, I do not know a third of this pure and well-like character. Successive nations

16:31.920 --> 16:40.300
perchance have drank at, admired, and fathomed it, and passed away, and still its water is

16:40.300 --> 16:47.020
green and pollucid as ever. Not an intermitting spring.

16:48.180 --> 16:55.020
Perhaps on that spring morning when Adam and Eve were driven out of Eden, Walden Pond was

16:55.020 --> 17:01.300
already in existence, and even then breaking up in a gentle spring rain accompanied with

17:01.300 --> 17:08.480
mist and a southerly wind, and covered with myriads of ducks and geese which had not heard

17:08.480 --> 17:17.000
of the fall, when still such pure lakes sufficed them. Even then it had commenced to rise and

17:17.000 --> 17:23.740
fall, and had clarified its waters, and coloured them of the hue they now wear, and obtained

17:23.740 --> 17:33.060
a patent of heaven to be the only Walden Pond in the world, and distiller of celestial dews.

17:34.440 --> 17:44.040
Who knows in how many unremembered nations' literatures this has been the Castilian Fountain,

17:44.700 --> 17:53.040
or what nymphs presided over it in the Golden Age. It is a gem of the first water which

17:53.040 --> 18:02.700
Concord wears in her coronet. Yet, perchance, the first who came to this well have left

18:02.700 --> 18:09.000
some trace of their footsteps. I have been surprised to detect, in circling the pond,

18:09.000 --> 18:16.320
even where a thick wood has just been cut down on the shore, a narrow shelf-like path

18:16.320 --> 18:23.600
in the steep hillside, alternately rising and falling, approaching and receding from

18:23.600 --> 18:31.520
the water's edge, as old probably as the race of man here, worn by the feet of aboriginal

18:31.520 --> 18:37.780
hunters, and still from time to time unwittingly trodden by the present occupants of the land.

18:39.340 --> 18:45.340
This is particularly distinct to one standing on the middle of the pond in winter, just

18:45.340 --> 18:53.580
after a light snow has fallen, appearing as a clear undulating white line, unobscured

18:53.580 --> 18:59.880
by weeds and twigs, and very obvious a quarter of a mile off in many places where in summer

18:59.880 --> 19:07.820
it is hardly distinguishable close at hand. The snow reprints it, as it were, in clear

19:07.820 --> 19:18.620
white type alto relivo. The ornamented grounds of villas which will one day be built here

19:18.620 --> 19:28.460
may still preserve some trace of this. The pond rises and falls, but whether regularly

19:28.460 --> 19:36.820
or not, and within what period, nobody knows, though as usual many pretend to know, it is

19:36.820 --> 19:42.100
commonly higher in winter and lower in the summer, though not corresponding to the general

19:42.100 --> 19:48.940
wet and dryness. I can remember when it was a foot or two lower, and also when it was

19:48.940 --> 19:56.600
at least five feet higher, than when I lived by it. There is a narrow sand bar running

19:56.600 --> 20:03.300
into it, with very deep water on one side, on which I helped boil a kettle of chowder,

20:03.300 --> 20:10.680
some six rods from the main shore, about the year 1824, which it has not been possible

20:10.680 --> 20:17.620
to do for twenty-five years. And, on the other hand, my friends used to listen with incredulity

20:17.620 --> 20:23.120
when I told them that a few years later I was accustomed to fish from a boat in a secluded

20:23.120 --> 20:30.900
cove in the woods, fifteen rods from the only shore they knew, which place was long since

20:30.900 --> 20:38.420
converted into a meadow. But the pond has risen steadily for two years, and now, in

20:38.420 --> 20:45.160
the summer of 52, is just five feet higher than when I lived there, or as high as it

20:45.160 --> 20:52.820
was thirty years ago, and fishing goes on again in the meadow. This makes a difference

20:52.820 --> 21:00.300
of level at the outside of six or seven feet, and yet the watershed by the surrounding hills

21:00.300 --> 21:06.400
is insignificant in amount, and this overflow must be referred to causes which affect the

21:06.400 --> 21:07.520
deep springs.

21:09.760 --> 21:16.260
This same summer the pond has begun to fall again. It is remarkable that this fluctuation,

21:16.700 --> 21:21.800
whether periodical or not, appears thus to require many years for its accomplishment.

21:22.520 --> 21:28.980
I have observed one rise and a part of two falls, and I expect that a dozen or fifteen

21:28.980 --> 21:33.480
years hence the water will again be as low as I have ever known it.

21:34.800 --> 21:40.840
Flint's pond a mile eastward, allowing for the disturbance occasioned by its inlets and

21:40.840 --> 21:49.220
outlets and the smaller intermediate ponds also, sympathize with Walden, and recently

21:49.220 --> 21:55.720
attained their greatest height at the same time with the latter. The same is true as

21:55.720 --> 21:59.220
far as my observation goes of White Pond.

22:01.220 --> 22:07.940
This rise and fall of Walden at long intervals serves this use at least. The water standing

22:07.940 --> 22:13.620
at this great height for a year or more, though it makes it difficult to walk round it, kills

22:13.620 --> 22:20.060
the shrubs and trees which have sprung up about its edge since the last rise. Pitch

22:20.060 --> 22:27.560
pines, birches, alders, aspens, and others, and falling again leaves an unobstructed shore,

22:28.320 --> 22:34.980
for unlike many ponds, and all waters which are subject to a daily tide, its shore is

22:34.980 --> 22:37.080
cleanest when the water is lowest.

22:39.440 --> 22:46.460
On the side of the pond, next my house, a row of pitch pines fifteen feet high has been

22:46.460 --> 22:53.140
killed and tipped over as if by a lever, and thus a stop put to their encroachments,

22:54.340 --> 22:59.160
and their size indicates how many years have elapsed since the last rise to this height.

23:00.820 --> 23:07.480
By this fluctuation the pond asserts its title to a shore, and thus the shore is shorn,

23:08.220 --> 23:15.200
and the trees cannot hold it by right of possession. These are the lips of the lake on which no

23:15.200 --> 23:22.840
beard grows. It licks its chaps from time to time. When the weather is at its height

23:22.840 --> 23:29.880
the alders, willows, and maples send forth a mass of fibrous red roots, several feet

23:29.880 --> 23:35.320
long from all sides of their stems in the water, and to the height of three or four

23:35.320 --> 23:42.600
feet from the ground, in the effort to maintain themselves. And I have known the high blueberry

23:42.600 --> 23:48.820
bushes about the shore, which commonly produce no fruit, bear an abundant crop under these

23:48.820 --> 23:56.980
circumstances. Some have been puzzled to tell how the shore became so regularly paved.

23:58.620 --> 24:04.360
My townsmen have all heard the tradition, the oldest people tell me that they heard

24:04.360 --> 24:12.580
it in their youth, that anciently the Indians were holding a powwow upon a hill here, which

24:12.580 --> 24:19.360
rose as high into the heavens as the pond now sinks deep into the earth. And they used

24:19.360 --> 24:25.560
much profanity, as the story goes, though this vice is one of which the Indians were

24:25.560 --> 24:32.220
never guilty, and while they were thus engaged the hill shook and suddenly sank, and only

24:32.220 --> 24:41.160
one old squaw, named Walden, escaped, and from her the pond was named. It has been conjectured

24:41.160 --> 24:46.860
that when the hill shook these stones rolled down its side and became the present shore.

24:48.280 --> 24:55.100
It is very certain, at any rate, that once there was no pond here, and now there is one,

24:55.700 --> 25:01.640
and this Indian fable does not in any respect conflict with the account of the ancient settler,

25:01.920 --> 25:07.100
whom I have mentioned, who remembers so well when he first came here with his divining

25:07.100 --> 25:14.880
rod, saw a thin vapor rising from the sward, and the hazel pointed steadily downward, and

25:14.880 --> 25:22.740
he concluded to dig a well here. As for the stones, many still think that they are hardly

25:22.740 --> 25:29.480
to be accounted for by the action of the waves on these hills, but I observe that the surrounding

25:29.480 --> 25:36.100
hills are remarkably full of the same kind of stones, so that they have been obliged

25:36.100 --> 25:42.700
to pile them up in walls on both sides of the railroad cut nearest the pond, and moreover

25:42.700 --> 25:50.780
there are more stones where the shore is most abrupt, so that unfortunately it is no longer

25:50.780 --> 25:59.460
a mystery to me. I detect the paver. If the name was not derived from that of some English

25:59.460 --> 26:07.660
locality, Safran Walden, for instance, one might suppose that it was called originally

26:07.660 --> 26:20.000
Walled Inn Pond. The pond was my well, ready dug. For four months in the year its water

26:20.000 --> 26:26.520
is as cold as it is pure at all times, and I think that it is then as good as any if

26:26.520 --> 26:33.680
not the best in the town. In the winter all water which is exposed to the air is colder

26:33.680 --> 26:39.480
than springs and wells which are protected from it. The temperature of the pond water,

26:39.760 --> 26:44.400
which had stood in the room where I sat from five o'clock in the afternoon till noon the

26:44.400 --> 26:54.140
next day, the sixth of March, 1846, the thermometer having been up to 65 or 70 degrees some of

26:54.140 --> 27:00.900
the time, owing partly to the sun on the roof, was 42 degrees, or one degree colder

27:00.900 --> 27:04.740
than the water of one of the coldest wells in the village just drawn.

27:06.160 --> 27:13.700
The temperature of the boiling spring the same day was 45 degrees, or the warmest of

27:13.700 --> 27:20.900
any water tried, though it is the coldest that I know of in summer, when beside shallow

27:20.900 --> 27:29.720
stagnant surface water is not mingled with it. Moreover, in summer Walden never becomes

27:29.720 --> 27:36.520
so warm as most water which is exposed to the sun on account of its depth. In the warmest

27:36.520 --> 27:43.020
weather I usually placed a pailful in my cellar where it became cool in the night and remained

27:43.020 --> 27:49.860
so during the day, though I also resorted to a spring in the neighborhood. It was as

27:49.860 --> 27:54.860
good when a week old as the day it was dipped and had no taste of the pump.

27:56.680 --> 28:02.140
Whoever camps for a week in summer by the shore of a pond needs only bury a pail of

28:02.140 --> 28:08.960
water a few feet deep in the shade of his camp to be independent of the luxury of ice.

28:10.800 --> 28:16.720
There have been caught in Walden pickerel, one weighing seven pounds. To say nothing

28:16.720 --> 28:22.020
of another which carried off a reel with great velocity, which the fisherman safely

28:22.020 --> 28:28.540
set down at eight pounds because he did not see him. Perch and pouts, some of each weighing

28:28.540 --> 28:38.360
over two pounds, shiners, chivins or roach, a very few breams, and a couple of eels, one

28:38.360 --> 28:44.080
weighing four pounds. I am thus particular because the weight of a fish is commonly its

28:44.080 --> 28:52.040
only title to fame, and these are the only eels I have heard of here. Also I have a faint

28:52.040 --> 28:59.360
recollection of a little fish some five inches long, with silvery sides and a greenish back,

29:00.220 --> 29:06.380
somewhat dais-like in its character, which I mention here chiefly to link my facts to

29:06.380 --> 29:06.940
fable.

29:08.580 --> 29:14.860
Nevertheless, this pond is not very fertile in fish. Its pickerel, though not abundant,

29:15.280 --> 29:22.500
are its chief boast. I have seen at one time, lying on the ice, pickerel of at least three

29:22.500 --> 29:36.920
different kinds, a long and shallow one, steel-colored, most like those caught in the river, a bright

29:36.920 --> 29:43.660
common here, and another golden-colored and shaped like the last, but peppered on the

29:43.660 --> 29:50.360
sides with small dark brown or black spots intermixed with a few faint blood-red ones,

29:50.800 --> 30:00.160
very much like a trout. The specific name reticulatus would not apply to this. It should

30:00.160 --> 30:09.900
be guttatus, rather. These are all very firm fish, and way more than their size promises.

30:10.940 --> 30:19.000
The shiners, pouts, and perch also, and indeed all the fishes which inhabit this pond, are

30:19.000 --> 30:26.800
much cleaner, handsomer, and firmer-fleshed than those in the river, and most other ponds,

30:26.980 --> 30:34.360
as the water is purer, and they can easily be distinguished from them. Probably many

30:34.360 --> 30:41.140
ichthyologists would make new varieties of some of them. There are also a certain race

30:41.140 --> 30:50.540
of frogs and tortoises, and a few mussels in it. Muskrats and mink leave their traces

30:50.540 --> 30:58.600
about it, and occasionally a travelling mud-turtle visits it. Sometimes, when I pushed off my

30:58.600 --> 31:04.540
boat in the morning, I disturbed a great mud-turtle which had secreted himself under the boat

31:04.540 --> 31:11.440
in the night. Ducks and geese frequent it in the spring and fall, the white-bellied

31:11.440 --> 31:20.520
swallows, hereundo bicolor, skim over it, and the peat-wheats, Totanus macularius, which

31:20.920 --> 31:27.560
is the name of this species, teeter along its stony shores all summer. I have sometimes

31:27.560 --> 31:34.400
disturbed a fish-hawk sitting on a white pine over the water, but I doubt if it is ever

31:34.400 --> 31:43.940
profaned by the wind of a gull, like Fairhaven. At most it tolerates one annual loon. These

31:43.940 --> 31:47.560
are all the animals of consequence which frequent it now.

31:48.940 --> 31:55.040
You may see from a boat, in calm weather, near the sandy eastern shore, where the water

31:55.040 --> 32:01.100
is eight or ten feet deep, and also in some other parts of the pond, some circular heaps

32:01.100 --> 32:07.320
half a dozen feet in diameter, by a foot in height, consisting of small stones less than

32:07.880 --> 32:16.100
in size, where all around is bare sand. At first you wonder if the Indians could have

32:16.100 --> 32:21.720
formed them on the ice for any purpose, and so when the ice melted they sank to the bottom,

32:22.600 --> 32:29.480
but they are too regular and some of them plainly too fresh for that. They are similar

32:29.480 --> 32:37.080
to those found in rivers, but as there are no suckers nor lampreys here, I know not by

32:37.080 --> 32:44.580
what fish they could be made. Perhaps they are the nests of the chiven. These lend a

32:44.580 --> 32:46.560
pleasing mystery to the bottom.

32:48.240 --> 32:56.640
The shore is irregular enough not to be monotonous. I have in my mind's eye the western, indented

32:56.640 --> 33:07.060
with deep bays, the bolder northern, and the beautifully scalloped southern shore, where

33:07.060 --> 33:14.700
men suggest unexplored coves between. The forest was never so good a setting, nor is

33:14.700 --> 33:21.140
so distinctly beautiful, as when seen from the middle of a small lake, amid hills which

33:21.140 --> 33:27.680
rise from the water's edge. For the water in which it is reflected not only makes the

33:27.680 --> 33:34.640
best foreground in such a case, but with its winding shore the most natural and agreeable

33:34.640 --> 33:43.400
boundary to it. There is no rawness nor imperfection in its edge there, as where the axe has cleared

33:43.400 --> 33:52.660
apart or a cultivated field abuts on it. The trees have ample room to expand on the water

33:52.660 --> 34:04.620
side, and each sends forth its most vigorous branch in that direction. There nature has

34:04.620 --> 34:12.000
just gradations from the low shrubs of the shore to the highest trees. There are few

34:12.000 --> 34:20.540
traces of man's hand to be seen. The water laves the shore as it did a thousand years

34:20.540 --> 34:21.020
ago.

34:23.000 --> 34:32.120
A lake is the landscape's most beautiful and expressive feature. It is earth's eye, looking

34:32.120 --> 34:41.820
into which the beholder measures the depth of his own nature. The fluvia-tiled trees

34:41.820 --> 34:49.480
next the shore are the slender eyelashes which fringe it, and the wooded hills and cliffs

34:49.480 --> 34:58.380
around it are its overhanging brows. Standing on the smooth sandy beach at the east end

34:58.380 --> 35:05.540
of the pond in a calm September afternoon, when a slight haze makes the opposite shoreline

35:05.540 --> 35:16.160
indistinct, I have seen whence came the expression the glassy surface of a lake. When you invert

35:16.160 --> 35:27.420
your head it looks like a thread of finest gossamer stretched across the valley, and

35:27.420 --> 35:33.620
creating one stratum of the atmosphere from another. You would think that you could walk

35:33.620 --> 35:40.380
dry under it to the opposing hills, and that the swallows which skim over might perch on

35:40.380 --> 35:49.380
it. Indeed, they sometimes dive below this line as if it were by mistake, and are undeceived.

35:49.380 --> 35:57.720
As you look over the pond westward you are obliged to employ both your hands to defend

35:57.720 --> 36:04.240
your eyes against the reflected as well as the true sun, for they are equally bright.

36:04.930 --> 36:13.080
And if between the two you survey its surface critically, it is literally as smooth as glass,

36:13.720 --> 36:22.380
except where the skater insects at equal intervals scatter over its whole extent, by their motions

36:22.380 --> 36:31.280
in the sun produce the finest imaginable sparkle on it. Or, perchance, a duck plumes itself,

36:32.220 --> 36:38.240
or as I have said, a swallow skims so low as to touch it.

36:39.060 --> 36:47.680
It may be that in the distance a fish describes an arc of three or four feet in the air, and

36:47.680 --> 36:56.020
there is one bright flash where it emerges, and another where it strikes the water. Sometimes

36:56.020 --> 37:04.340
the whole silvery arc is revealed, or here and there, perhaps, is a thistle down floating

37:04.340 --> 37:13.560
on its surface, which the fishes dart at, and so dimple it again. It is like molten

37:13.560 --> 37:22.980
glass, cooled, but not congealed, and the few motes in it are pure and beautiful like

37:22.980 --> 37:32.300
the imperfections in glass. You may often detect a yet smoother and darker water, separated

37:32.300 --> 37:43.800
from the rest, as if by an invisible cobweb, boom of the water nymphs resting on it. From

37:43.800 --> 37:51.260
a hilltop you can see a fish leap in almost any part, for not a pickerel or shiner picks

37:51.260 --> 38:02.280
an insect from this smooth surface, but it manifestly disturbs the equilibrium of the

38:02.280 --> 38:12.960
what elaborateness this simple fact is advertised. This piscine murder will out, and from my

38:12.960 --> 38:20.680
distant perch I distinguish the circling undulations, when they are half a dozen rods in diameter.

38:22.240 --> 38:29.880
You can even detect a water bug, Gyrannus, ceaselessly progressing over the smooth surface

38:29.880 --> 38:37.740
a quarter of a mile off, for they furrow the water slightly, making a conspicuous ripple

38:37.740 --> 38:45.680
bounded by two diverging lines, but the skaters glide over it without rippling it perceptibly.

38:46.980 --> 38:52.980
When the surface is considerably agitated there are no skaters nor water bugs on it,

38:53.380 --> 39:00.700
but apparently, in calm days, they leave their havens and adventurously glide forth from

39:00.700 --> 39:09.800
the shore by short impulses till they completely cover it. It is a soothing employment on one

39:09.800 --> 39:16.460
of those fine days in the fall, when all the warmth of the sun is fully appreciated, to

39:16.460 --> 39:23.830
sit on a stump on such a height as this, overlooking the pond, and study the dimpling circles,

39:24.980 --> 39:32.200
which are incessantly inscribed on its otherwise invisible surface, amid the reflected skies

39:32.200 --> 39:40.840
and trees. Over this great expanse there is no disturbance, but it is thus at once gently

39:40.840 --> 39:49.880
smoothed away and assaged, as when a vase of water is jarred the trembling circles seek

39:49.880 --> 39:57.840
the shore and all is smooth again. Not a fish can leap or an insect fall on the pond, but

39:57.840 --> 40:06.120
it is thus reported in circling dimples, in lines of beauty, as it were the constant welling

40:06.120 --> 40:15.360
up of its fountain, the gentle pulsing of its life, the heaving of its breast. The thrills

40:15.360 --> 40:26.900
of joy and thrills of pain are indistinguishable. How peaceful the phenomena of the lake! Again

40:26.900 --> 40:29.900
the works of man shine as in the spring.

40:31.700 --> 40:39.720
Ay, every leaf and twig and stone and cobweb sparkles now at mid-afternoon, as when covered

40:39.720 --> 40:49.620
with dew in a spring morning. Every motion of an oar or an insect produces a flash of

40:49.620 --> 40:55.340
light, and if an oar falls, how sweet the echo!

40:56.660 --> 41:06.900
In such a day, in September or October, Walden is a perfect forest mirror, set round with

41:06.900 --> 41:17.520
stones as precious to my eye as if fewer or rarer. Nothing so fair, so pure, and at the

41:17.520 --> 41:25.320
same time so large as a lake, perchance, lies on the surface of the earth. Sky, water, and

41:25.340 --> 41:37.440
water. It needs no fence. Nations come and go without defiling it. It is a mirror which

41:37.440 --> 41:48.820
no stone can crack, whose quick silver will never wear off, whose gilding nature continually

41:48.820 --> 42:03.220
repairs. No storms, no dust can dim its surface ever fresh. A mirror in which all impurity

42:03.220 --> 42:16.100
presented to it sinks, swept and dusted by the sun's hazy brush. This, the light dust

42:16.100 --> 42:25.800
cloth, which retains no breath that has breathed on it, but sends its own to float as clouds

42:25.800 --> 42:35.240
high above its surface and be reflected in its bosom still. A field of water betrays

42:35.240 --> 42:42.060
the spirit that is in the air. It is continually receiving new life and motion from above.

42:42.060 --> 42:51.860
It is intermediate in its nature between land and sky. On land only the grass and trees

42:51.860 --> 43:01.380
wave, but the water itself is rippled by the wind. I see where the breeze dashes across

43:01.380 --> 43:09.040
it by the streaks or flakes of light. It is remarkable that we can look down on its surface.

43:09.040 --> 43:19.980
We shall, perhaps, look down thus on the surface of air at length, and mark where a still subtler

43:19.980 --> 43:29.280
spirit sweeps over it. The skaters and water bugs finally disappear in the latter part

43:29.280 --> 43:38.260
of October, when the severe frosts have come. And then, and in November, usually in a calm

43:38.260 --> 43:43.980
day, there is absolutely nothing to ripple the surface.

43:45.340 --> 43:52.700
One November afternoon, in the calm at the end of a rainstorm of several days' duration,

43:53.800 --> 44:01.600
when the sky was still completely overcast and the air was full of mist, I observed that

44:01.600 --> 44:08.540
the pond was remarkably smooth, so that it was difficult to distinguish its surface,

44:09.520 --> 44:16.200
though it no longer reflected the bright tints of October, but the somber November colors

44:16.200 --> 44:23.140
of the surrounding hills. Though I passed over it as gently as possible,

44:23.500 --> 44:31.120
the slight undulations produced by my boat extended almost as far as I could see.

44:31.600 --> 44:41.100
And gave a ribbed appearance to the reflections. But, as I was looking over the surface, I

44:41.100 --> 44:50.600
saw here and there at a distance a faint glimmer, as if some skater insects which had escaped

44:50.600 --> 45:00.420
the frosts might be collected there, or, perchance, the surface, being so smoothed, betrayed where

45:00.420 --> 45:06.240
a spring welled up from the bottom, paddling gently to one of these places.

45:07.200 --> 45:15.380
I was surprised to find myself surrounded by myriads of small perch, about five inches

45:15.380 --> 45:22.920
long, of a rich bronze color in the green water, sporting there and constantly rising

45:22.920 --> 45:28.040
to the surface and dimpling it, sometimes leaving bubbles on it.

45:28.040 --> 45:36.920
In such transparent and seemingly bottomless water, reflecting the clouds, I seemed to

45:36.920 --> 45:43.640
be floating through the air as in a balloon, and their swimming impressed me as a kind

45:43.640 --> 45:52.980
of flight or hovering, as if they were a compact flock of birds passing just beneath my level

45:52.980 --> 46:00.360
on the right or left. Their fins, like sails, set all around them.

46:01.900 --> 46:08.600
There were many such schools in the pond, apparently improving the short season before

46:08.600 --> 46:16.460
winter would draw an icy shutter over their broad skylight, sometimes giving to the surface

46:16.460 --> 46:23.920
an appearance as if a slight breeze struck it, or a few raindrops fell there. When I

46:23.920 --> 46:29.640
approached carelessly and alarmed them, they made a sudden splash and rippling with their

46:29.640 --> 46:36.040
tails as if one had struck the water with a bushy bow, and instantly took refuge in

46:36.040 --> 46:36.660
the depths.

46:38.260 --> 46:46.440
At length the wind rose, the mist increased, and the waves began to run, and the plume

46:46.460 --> 46:54.320
perch leaped much higher than before, half out of water, a hundred black points, three

46:54.320 --> 46:57.920
inches long, at once above the surface.

46:59.660 --> 47:05.420
Even as late as the fifth of December one year I saw some dimples on the surface and

47:05.420 --> 47:12.880
thinking it was going to rain hard immediately, the air being full of mist. I made haste to

47:12.880 --> 47:18.820
take my place at the oars and row homeward. Already the rain seemed rapidly increasing,

47:19.420 --> 47:26.600
though I felt none on my cheek, and I anticipated a thorough soaking. But suddenly the dimples

47:26.600 --> 47:34.060
ceased, for they were produced by the perch, which the noise of my oars had seared into

47:34.060 --> 47:42.220
the depths, and I saw their schools dimly disappearing. So I spent a dry afternoon after

47:42.220 --> 47:42.640
all.

47:43.430 --> 47:49.460
An old man who used to frequent this pond nearly sixty years ago, when it was dark with

47:49.460 --> 47:55.980
surrounding forests, tells me that in those days he sometimes saw it all alive with ducks

47:55.980 --> 48:03.280
and other water fowl, and that there were many eagles about it. He came here fishing

48:03.280 --> 48:11.460
and used an old log canoe which he found on the shore. It was made of two white pine logs

48:11.460 --> 48:18.940
dug out and pinned together, and was cut off square at the ends. It was very clumsy,

48:19.800 --> 48:25.040
but lasted a great many years before it became waterlogged and perhaps sank to the bottom.

48:26.560 --> 48:33.840
He did not know whose it was. It belonged to the pond. He used to make a cable for his

48:33.840 --> 48:36.760
anchor of strips of hickory bark tied together.

48:38.220 --> 48:45.860
An old man, a potter who lived by the pond before the revolution, told him once that

48:45.860 --> 48:52.600
there was an iron chest at the bottom, and that he had seen it. Sometimes it would come

48:52.600 --> 48:57.600
floating up to the shore, but when you went toward it, it would go back into the deep

48:57.600 --> 48:58.840
water and disappear.

49:00.620 --> 49:07.340
I was pleased to hear of the old log canoe, which took the place of an Indian one of the

49:07.340 --> 49:13.740
same material but more graceful construction, which perchance had first been a tree on the

49:13.740 --> 49:21.420
bank, and then as it were fell into the water to float there for a generation, the most

49:21.420 --> 49:23.080
proper vessel for the lake.

49:24.660 --> 49:31.240
I remember that when I first looked into these depths there were many large trunks to be

49:31.240 --> 49:37.700
seen indistinctly lying on the bottom, which had either been blown over formerly, or left

49:37.700 --> 49:44.200
on the ice at the last cutting, when wood was cheaper, but now they have mostly disappeared.

49:45.700 --> 49:53.240
When I first paddled a boat on Walden it was completely surrounded by thick and lofty pine

49:53.240 --> 50:00.720
and oak woods, and in some of its coves grape vines had run over the trees next the water,

50:01.400 --> 50:08.740
and formed bowers under which a boat could pass. The hills which form its shores are

50:08.740 --> 50:14.700
so steep, and the woods on them then so high, that as you looked down from the west end

50:14.700 --> 50:21.400
it had the appearance of an amphitheatre for some land of sylvan spectacle.

50:22.680 --> 50:29.840
I have spent many an hour, when I was younger, floating over its surface as the Zephyr willed,

50:30.660 --> 50:37.000
having paddled my boat to the middle, and lying on my back across the seats in a summer

50:37.000 --> 50:45.760
forenoon, dreaming awake, until I was aroused by the boat touching the sand, and I arose

50:45.760 --> 50:53.820
to see what shore my fates had impelled me to, days when idleness was the most attractive

50:53.820 --> 51:02.440
and productive industry. Many a forenoon have I stolen away, preferring to spend thus the

51:02.440 --> 51:13.000
most valued part of the day, for I was rich, if not in money, in sunny hours and summer

51:13.000 --> 51:23.320
days, and spent them lavishly. Nor do I regret that I did not waste more of them in the workshop

51:23.320 --> 51:31.240
or the teacher's desk, but since I left those shores the woodchoppers have still further

51:31.240 --> 51:38.100
laid them waste, and now for many a year there will be no more rambling through the aisles

51:38.100 --> 51:46.800
of the wood, with occasional vistas through which you see the water. My muse may be excused

51:46.800 --> 51:56.340
if she is silent henceforth. How can you expect the birds to sing when their groves are cut

51:56.340 --> 52:04.680
down? Now the trunks of trees on the bottom, and the old log canoe, and the dark surrounding

52:04.680 --> 52:12.840
woods are gone, and the villagers, who scarcely know where it lies, instead of going to the

52:12.840 --> 52:19.720
pond to bathe or drink, are thinking to bring its water, which should be as sacred as the

52:19.720 --> 52:29.520
mangies at least, to the village in a pipe, to wash their dishes with, to earn their Walden

52:29.520 --> 52:39.460
by the turning of a cock or the drawing of a plug. That devilish iron horse, whose ear

52:39.460 --> 52:45.920
rending neigh is heard throughout the town, has muddied the boiling spring with his foot,

52:46.350 --> 52:54.600
and here it is that has browsed off all the woods on Walden shore, that Trojan horse with

52:54.600 --> 53:03.960
a thousand men in his belly, introduced by mercenary Greeks. Where is the country's champion,

53:05.080 --> 53:13.040
the moor of Moor Hill, to meet him at the deep cut and thrust an avenging lance between

53:13.040 --> 53:22.560
the ribs of the bloated pest? Nevertheless, of all the characters I have known, perhaps

53:22.560 --> 53:31.840
Walden wears best, and best preserves its purity. Many men have been likened to it,

53:32.220 --> 53:39.840
but few deserve that honor. Though the woodchoppers have laid bare first this shore and then that,

53:40.120 --> 53:47.420
and the Irish have built their sties by it, and the railroad has infringed on its border,

53:48.220 --> 53:57.800
and the ice-men have skimmed it once, it is itself unchanged. The same water which my

53:57.800 --> 54:08.620
youthful eyes fell on, all the change is in me. It has not acquired one permanent wrinkle

54:08.620 --> 54:20.620
after all its ripples. It is perennially young, and I may stand and see a swallow-dip apparently

54:20.620 --> 54:29.920
to pick an insect from its surface as of yore. It struck me again tonight, as if I had not

54:29.920 --> 54:38.600
seen it almost daily for more than twenty years. Why, here is Walden, the same woodchopper

54:38.620 --> 54:47.340
woodland lake that I discovered so many years ago, where a forest was cut down last winter,

54:48.120 --> 54:55.320
another is springing up by its shore as lustily as ever. The same thought is welling up to

54:55.320 --> 55:05.520
its surface that was then. It is the same liquid joy and happiness to itself and its

55:05.520 --> 55:17.460
maker, I, and it may be to me. It is the work of a brave man, surely, in whom there was

55:17.460 --> 55:27.140
no guile. He rounded this water with his hand, deepened and clarified it in his thought,

55:28.000 --> 55:35.500
and in his will bequeathed it to Concord. I see but one thing, and that is that the

55:35.520 --> 55:42.300
water is filled by its face, that it is visited by the same reflection, and I can almost say,

55:43.560 --> 55:46.160
Walden, is it you?

55:50.060 --> 55:59.460
It is no dream of mine to ornament a line. I cannot come nearer to God and heaven than

55:59.460 --> 56:10.460
I live to Walden even. I am its stony shore, and the breeze that passes o'er in the hollow

56:10.460 --> 56:20.720
of my hand are its water and its sand, and its deepest resort lies high in my thought.

56:23.080 --> 56:30.280
The cars never pause to look at it, yet I fancy that the engineers and firemen and brakemen

56:30.280 --> 56:36.960
and those passengers who have a season ticket and see it often are better men for the sight.

56:38.100 --> 56:46.800
The engineer does not forget at night, or his nature does not, that he has held this

56:46.800 --> 56:58.060
vision of serenity and purity once at least during the day. Though seen but once, it helps

56:58.060 --> 57:06.820
to wash out State Street and the engine's soot. One proposes that it be called God's

57:06.820 --> 57:07.160
Drop.

57:09.340 --> 57:16.780
I have said that Walden has no visible inlet nor outlet, but it is on the one hand the

57:16.800 --> 57:23.900
distantly and indirectly related to Flint's Pond, which is more elevated, by a chain of

57:23.900 --> 57:30.460
small ponds coming from that quarter, and on the other directly and manifestly to Concord

57:30.460 --> 57:37.760
River, which is lower, by a similar chain of ponds, through which in some other geological

57:37.760 --> 57:45.540
period it may have flowed, and by a little digging, which, God forbid, it can be made

57:45.540 --> 57:54.120
to flow thither again. If by living thus reserved and austere like a hermit in the woods so

57:54.120 --> 58:02.200
long it has acquired such wonderful purity, who would not regret that the comparatively

58:02.200 --> 58:09.500
impure waters of Flint's Pond should be mingled with it, or itself should ever go to waste

58:09.500 --> 58:11.880
its sweetness in the ocean's wave?

58:14.840 --> 58:22.280
Flint's or Sandy Pond, in Lincoln, our greatest lake and inland sea, lies about a mile east

58:22.280 --> 58:30.120
of Walden. It is much larger, being said to contain 197 acres, and is more fertile than

58:30.120 --> 58:37.600
fish, but it is comparatively shallow and not remarkably pure. A walk through the woods

58:37.600 --> 58:44.800
thither was often my recreation. It was worth the while, if only to feel the wind blow on

58:44.800 --> 58:52.880
your cheeks freely, and see the waves run, and remember the life of mariners. I went

58:52.880 --> 58:58.100
a chestnutting there in the fall on windy days, when the nuts were dropping into the

58:58.100 --> 59:06.320
water and were washed to my feet, and one day as I crept along its sedgy shore the fresh

59:06.320 --> 59:14.200
spray blowing in my face I came upon the moldering wreck of a boat, the sides gone, and hardly

59:14.200 --> 59:20.380
more than the impression of its flat bottom left amid the rushes, yet its model was sharply

59:20.380 --> 59:28.980
defined as if it were a large decayed pad with its veins. It was as impressive a wreck

59:28.980 --> 59:36.300
as one could imagine on the seashore, and had as good a moral. It is by this time mere

59:36.300 --> 59:42.640
vegetable mold and undistinguishable pond-shore, through which rushes and flags have pushed

59:42.640 --> 59:49.700
up. I used to admire the ripple marks on the sandy bottom at the north end of this pond,

59:50.960 --> 59:57.240
made firm and hard to the feet of the wader by the pressure of the water, and the rushes

59:57.240 --> 01:00:05.320
which grew in Indian file in waving lines corresponding to these marks rank behind rank,

01:00:05.640 --> 01:00:13.180
as if the waves had planted them. There also I have found in considerable quantities curious

01:00:14.080 --> 01:00:22.940
balls composed apparently of fine grass or roots of pipewort perhaps, from half an inch

01:00:22.940 --> 01:00:30.260
to four inches in diameter, and perfectly spherical. They wash back and forth in shallow

01:00:30.260 --> 01:00:37.160
water on a sandy bottom, and are sometimes cast on the shore. They are either solid grass

01:00:37.160 --> 01:00:43.060
or have a little sand in the middle. At first you would say that they were formed by the

01:00:43.060 --> 01:00:50.100
action of the waves, like a pebble. Yet the smallest are made of equally coarse materials,

01:00:51.120 --> 01:00:57.960
half an inch long, and they are produced only at one season of the year. Moreover, the waves,

01:00:57.960 --> 01:01:04.300
I suspect, do not so much construct as wear down a material which has already acquired

01:01:04.300 --> 01:01:10.240
consistency. They preserve their form when dry for an indefinite period.

01:01:12.360 --> 01:01:13.780
Flint's Pond

01:01:14.700 --> 01:01:26.080
Such is the poverty of our nomenclature. What right had the unclean and stupid farmer whose

01:01:26.440 --> 01:01:35.100
shores he has ruthlessly laid bare to give his name to it? Some skin-flint who loved

01:01:35.100 --> 01:01:40.520
better the reflecting surface of a dollar or a bright scent in which he could see his

01:01:40.520 --> 01:01:47.260
own brazen face, who regarded even the wild ducks which settled in it as trespassers,

01:01:48.260 --> 01:01:55.720
his fingers grown into crooked and bony talons from the long habit of grasping harpy-like

01:01:56.080 --> 01:02:06.260
things? So it is not named for me. I go not there to see him nor to hear of him who never

01:02:06.260 --> 01:02:15.020
saw it, who never bathed in it, who never loved it, who never protected it, who never

01:02:15.020 --> 01:02:23.940
spoke a good word for it, nor thanked God that he had made it. Rather let it be named

01:02:23.940 --> 01:02:30.860
from the fishes that swim in it, the wild fowl or quadrupeds which frequent it, the

01:02:30.860 --> 01:02:39.080
wild flowers which grow by its shore, or some wild man or child the thread of whose history

01:02:39.080 --> 01:02:46.280
is interwoven with its own, not for him who could show no title to it but the deed which

01:02:46.280 --> 01:02:53.480
a like-minded neighbour or legislature gave him, him who thought only of its money value.

01:02:54.360 --> 01:03:02.300
Whose presence perchance cursed all the shores, who exhausted the land around it and would

01:03:02.300 --> 01:03:09.220
feign have exhausted the waters within it, who regretted only that it was not English

01:03:09.220 --> 01:03:16.960
hay or cranberry meadow. There was nothing to redeem it forsooth in his eyes, and would

01:03:16.960 --> 01:03:23.920
have drained and sold it for the mud at its bottom. It did not turn his mill, nor did

01:03:23.940 --> 01:03:33.880
it, and it was no privilege to him to behold it. I respect not his labours, his farm where

01:03:33.880 --> 01:03:40.520
everything has its price, who would carry the landscape, who would carry his God to

01:03:40.520 --> 01:03:49.460
market if he could get anything for him, who goes to market for his God as it is, on whose

01:03:49.460 --> 01:03:57.980
farm nothing grows free, whose fields bear no crops, whose meadows no flowers, whose

01:03:57.980 --> 01:04:09.020
trees no fruits but dollars, who loves not the beauty of his fruits, whose fruits are

01:04:09.020 --> 01:04:19.440
not ripe for him till they are turned to dollars. Give me the poverty that enjoys the people

01:04:19.460 --> 01:04:28.880
true wealth. Farmers are respectable and interesting to me in proportion as they are poor, poor

01:04:28.880 --> 01:04:39.840
farmers. A model farm where the house stands like a fungus in a muck heap, chambers for

01:04:39.840 --> 01:04:47.100
men, horses, oxen, and swine, cleansed and uncleansed, all contiguous to one another,

01:04:48.020 --> 01:04:57.720
stocked with men, a great grease spot, redolent of manures and buttermilk, under a high state

01:04:57.720 --> 01:05:04.840
of cultivation being manured with the hearts and brains of men, as if you were to raise

01:05:04.840 --> 01:05:11.800
your potatoes in the churchyard. Such is a model farm.

01:05:13.620 --> 01:05:21.960
No, no, if the fairest features of the landscape are to be named after men, let them be the

01:05:21.960 --> 01:05:31.380
noblest and worthiest men alone. Let our lakes receive as true names at least as the Icarian

01:05:31.380 --> 01:05:38.060
Sea, where still the shore a brave attempt resounds.

01:05:40.080 --> 01:05:47.240
Goose-pond of small extent is on my way to Flint's. Fairhaven, an expanse of Concord

01:05:47.240 --> 01:05:54.100
River, said to contain some seventy acres, is a mile southwest, and White-pond, of about

01:05:54.100 --> 01:06:03.220
forty acres, is a mile and a half beyond Fairhaven. This is my lake country. These, with Concord

01:06:03.220 --> 01:06:11.040
River, are my water privileges, and night and day, year in, year out, they grind such

01:06:11.040 --> 01:06:13.460
grist as I carry to them.

01:06:15.100 --> 01:06:22.000
Since the woodcutters and the railroad I myself have profaned Walden. Perhaps the most attractive,

01:06:22.560 --> 01:06:32.420
if not the most beautiful of all our lakes, the gem of the woods, is White-pond, poor

01:06:32.420 --> 01:06:38.940
derived from the remarkable purity of its waters or the color of its sands. In these,

01:06:39.060 --> 01:06:46.640
as in other respects, however, it is a lesser twin of Walden. They are so much alike that

01:06:46.640 --> 01:06:53.260
you would say they must be connected underground. It has the same stony shore, and its waters

01:06:53.260 --> 01:07:00.680
are of the same hue. As at Walden, in sultry dog-day weather, looking down through the

01:07:00.680 --> 01:07:06.860
woods on some of its bays, which are not so deep, but that the reflection from the bottom

01:07:06.860 --> 01:07:15.960
tinges them, its waters are of a misty bluish-green or glaucus color. Many years since I used

01:07:15.960 --> 01:07:23.220
to go there to collect the sand by cartloads, to make sand paper with, and I have continued

01:07:23.220 --> 01:07:24.780
to visit it ever since.

01:07:26.120 --> 01:07:34.720
One who frequents it proposes to call it Virid Lake. Perhaps it might be called Yellow Pine

01:07:34.720 --> 01:07:42.060
Lake, from the following circumstance. About fifteen years ago you could see the top of

01:07:42.060 --> 01:07:49.760
a pitch pine, of the kind called Yellow Pine hereabouts, though it is not a distinct species,

01:07:50.500 --> 01:07:56.800
projecting above this surface in deep water, many rods from the shore. It was even supposed

01:07:56.800 --> 01:08:02.560
by some that the pond had sunk, and this was one of the primitive forest that formerly

01:08:02.560 --> 01:08:11.320
stood there. I find that even so long ago, as 1792, in a topographical description of

01:08:11.320 --> 01:08:17.060
the town of Concord, by one of its citizens, in the Collections of the Massachusetts Historical

01:08:17.060 --> 01:08:22.760
Society, the author, after speaking of Walden and White Ponds, adds,

01:08:24.320 --> 01:08:30.280
In the middle of the latter may be seen, when the water is very low, a tree, which appears

01:08:30.280 --> 01:08:36.360
as if it grew in the place where it now stands. Although the roots are fifty feet below the

01:08:36.360 --> 01:08:42.860
surface of the water, the top of this tree is broken off, and at the place measures fourteen

01:08:42.860 --> 01:08:49.640
inches in diameter. In the spring of 49 I talked with a man who lives nearest the pond

01:08:49.640 --> 01:08:56.700
in Sudbury, who told me that it was he who got out this tree ten or fifteen years before.

01:08:57.460 --> 01:09:02.340
As near as he could remember it stood twelve or fifteen rods from the shore where the water

01:09:02.340 --> 01:09:07.560
was thirty or forty feet deep. It was in the winter, and he had been getting out ice in

01:09:07.560 --> 01:09:12.080
the afternoon, and had resolved that in the afternoon, with the aid of his neighbours,

01:09:12.560 --> 01:09:18.760
he would take out the old yellow pine. He sawed a channel in the ice toward the shore

01:09:18.760 --> 01:09:25.520
and hauled it over and along and out on to the ice with oxen. But before he had gone

01:09:25.520 --> 01:09:36.800
far in his work he was surprised to find that it was wrong end upward, with the stumps of

01:09:36.800 --> 01:09:44.260
the small end firmly fastened in the sandy bottom. It was about a foot in diameter at

01:09:44.260 --> 01:09:50.880
the big end, and he had expected to get a good saw log, but it was so rotten as to be

01:09:50.880 --> 01:09:58.300
fit only for fuel, if for that. He had some of it in his shed then. There were marks of

01:09:58.300 --> 01:10:03.240
an axe and of woodpeckers on the butt. He thought that it might have been a dead tree

01:10:03.240 --> 01:10:08.600
on the shore, but was finally blown over into the pond, and after the top had been

01:10:09.180 --> 01:10:14.620
waterlogged, while the butt end was still dry and light, had drifted out and sunk wrong

01:10:14.620 --> 01:10:21.160
end up. His father, eighty years old, could not remember when it was not there. Several

01:10:21.160 --> 01:10:26.380
pretty large logs may still be seen lying on the bottom, where, owing to the undulation

01:10:26.380 --> 01:10:34.260
of the surface, they look like huge water-snakes in motion. This pond has rarely been profaned

01:10:34.260 --> 01:10:41.400
by a boat, for there is little in it to tempt a fisherman. Instead of the white lily, which

01:10:41.400 --> 01:10:48.940
requires mud, or the common sweet flag, the blue flag, Iris versicolor, grows thinly

01:10:48.940 --> 01:10:54.720
in the pure water, rising from the stony bottom all around the shore, where it is visited

01:10:54.720 --> 01:11:00.400
by hummingbirds in June, and the color both of its bluish blades and its flowers, and

01:11:00.400 --> 01:11:07.640
especially their reflections, is in singular harmony with the glaucus water. White pond

01:11:07.640 --> 01:11:24.700
and Walden are great crystals on the surface of the earth, lakes of light. If they were

01:11:24.700 --> 01:11:34.180
off by slaves, like precious stones, to adorn the heads of emperors, but being liquid and

01:11:34.180 --> 01:11:42.240
ample, and secured to us and our successors forever, we disregard them, and run after

01:11:42.240 --> 01:11:52.160
the diamond of Koh-i-Noor. They are too pure to have a market value. They contain no muck.

01:11:52.820 --> 01:12:01.160
How much more beautiful than our lives! How much more transparent than our characters

01:12:01.540 --> 01:12:12.700
are they! We never learned meanness of them. How much fairer than the pool before the farmer's

01:12:12.700 --> 01:12:22.140
door, in which his ducks swim! Hither the clean wild ducks come. Nature's beauty is

01:12:22.160 --> 01:12:31.200
nature has no human inhabitant who appreciates her. The birds with their plumage and their

01:12:31.200 --> 01:12:40.740
notes are in harmony with the flowers. But what youth or maiden conspires with the wild

01:12:40.740 --> 01:12:49.920
luxuriant beauty of nature? She flourishes most alone, far from the towns where they

01:12:49.920 --> 01:12:57.260
reside. Talk of heaven! You disgrace earth!

